Chapter 7 Non-Linear Regression Models

This is a tidymodels implementation of the code in Chapter 7 of Applied Predictive Modeling by Max Kuhn and Kjell Johnson1. I have already implemented all code and models from this chapter using mainly the caret package in a separate notebook, APM_7.Rmd. In that notebook I used the solTrainXtrans data set as the training data. This data set has already had a transformation applied to it (Box-Cox). In this notebook I have used the full data set (un-transformed) and did the Box-Cox transformation and data splitting myself using the appropriate recipe.

Setup

# Load packages:
library(AppliedPredictiveModeling)
library(caret)
library(tidyverse)
library(tidymodels)
library(patchwork)

# Load my functions:
source("/home/brian/R/dir/Util/bh_functions.R")

# Options:
theme_set(theme_bw())
options(digits = 4)

Load and Split Data

The tidymodels process has its own functions for splitting data. Combine the pre-split training and test data from the solubility data into one data frame, then use the tidymodels functions to split the data:

# Load data:
data(solubility)

# Combine the data sets (update the name of the outcome vectors to y so that they are the same).
# Also give the data frame a generic name.
df1 <- rbind(
  cbind(y = solTrainY, solTrainX), # training data
  cbind(y = solTestY, solTestX) # test data
)

# Split data:
set.seed(1)
splits <- initial_split(df1) # default prop is 3/4
df_train <- training(splits)
df_test <- testing((splits))

# Create folds for 10-fold cross-validation:
folds <- vfold_cv(df_train, v = 10)

7.1 Neural Networks

Training Data

Build a neural network and train using cross-validation:

# Recipe:
rec1 <-
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_BoxCox(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_predictors(), -all_outcomes(), threshold = 0.75) # same threshold as the `caret` model

# Model:
# I have set the `MaxNWts` argument in the `set_engine()` step. I used the same formula as the `caret` model in `APM_7_1.R`.
# I don't think it matters that I am using the number of columns in `df_train` rather than the number of columns left after
# filtering out correlated variables (as the `caret` model does). As long as the number `MaxNWts` argument is big enough
# it should be fine, and it should be since the number of columns in `df_train` has to be greater than or equal to the
# number of columns in the preprocessed data.
nn_mod <-
  mlp(hidden_units = tune(), penalty = tune(), epochs = 1000) %>% # same number of iterations as the `caret` model 
  set_engine("nnet", MaxNWts = 13 * (ncol(df_train) + 1) + 13 + 1) %>%
  set_mode("regression")

# Workflow:
workflow1 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = nn_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1)

# Create a tuning grid with the same candidate values as the `caret` model (in `APM_7.R`): 
nn_grid <- expand.grid(hidden_units = c(1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13), penalty = c(0, 0.01, 0.1))

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter7/data/nn_cv2.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  nn_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  nn_cv <-
    workflow1 %>%
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = nn_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(nn_cv, file1)
}

Plot CV results:

The results are similar to the caret workflow and text (Fig. 7.2, page 145).

Select the best model and store the training error:

nn_best <- nn_cv %>% 
  select_best("rmse")

# Store the training error:
rmse_train <- nn_cv %>% 
  show_best("rmse") %>% 
  pluck("mean", 1)

Testing Data

Fit a model using all of the training data and apply it to the test data:

# Finalize the workflow by updating it to use the best model:
final_wf <- 
  workflow1 %>% 
  finalize_workflow(nn_best)

# This extracts the parameters in the final model (this code is clunky, could probably be made simpler):
wf <- final_wf %>% workflows::pull_workflow_spec()
hidden_units <- wf$args$hidden_units[2] %>% as.character()
Subsetting quosures with `[` is deprecated as of rlang 0.4.0
Please use `quo_get_expr()` instead.
This warning is displayed once per session.
penalty <- wf$args$penalty[2] %>% as.character()

# Fit the final model using all of the training data and evaluate using the test data:
nn_fit_final <- 
  final_wf %>%
  last_fit(splits) 

# Store test error:
rmse_test <- nn_fit_final %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  pluck(".estimate")

Store the training and test RMSE values and parameters:

RMSE_TM <- tibble(
  framework = "tidymodels",
  engine = "nnet",
  model = "Neural Network",
  rmse_train = rmse_train,
  rmse_test = rmse_test,
  parameters = str_interp("hidden_units: ${hidden_units}; penalty: ${penalty}")
)

Use the predictions to make diagnostic plots

Collect the predictions from the final fit and make diagnostic plots:

preds <- nn_fit_final %>% 
  collect_predictions() %>% 
  mutate(residual = y - .pred)

p1 <- ggplot(preds) +
  geom_point(aes(.pred, y),
             color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_abline(color = "indianred1", linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_x_continuous("Predicted",
                     breaks = seq(-10, 0, by = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous("Observed",
                     breaks = seq(-10, 0, by = 2))

p2 <- ggplot(preds) +
  geom_point(aes(.pred, residual),
             color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
             color = "indianred1", linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_x_continuous("Predicted",
                     breaks = seq(-10, 0, by = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous("Residual")

p1 + p2 + plot_annotation(title = "Diagnostic Plots - Neural Network")

7.2 Multivariate Adaptive Regression Splines (MARS)

Training Data

Build a MARS model and train using cross-validation: (Run time: 9.07 mins)

# Recipe:
rec2 <-
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_BoxCox(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes())

# Model:
mars_mod <-
  mars(num_terms = tune(), prod_degree = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("earth") %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# Workflow:
workflow2 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = mars_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec2)

# Create a tuning grid with the same candidate values as the `caret` model (in `APM_7.R`): 
mars_grid <- expand.grid(num_terms = 2:38, prod_degree = 1:2)

start <- bh_start_timer()

if (file.exists(file1)) {
  mars_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  mars_cv <- 
    workflow1 %>% 
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = mars_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))

7.4 K-Nearest Neighbors

Training Data

Build a KNN model and train using cross-validation: (Run time: 2 mins)

  step_scale(all_predictors())
